subsection.p:
A tiny piece of area \Delta A near (x,y) has approximate mass \sigma(x,y)\,\Delta A. So the total mass should be m=\iint_D \sigma(x,y)\,dA. For this sign,
m \amp= \int_0^2\int_0^1 (1+x)\,dy\,dx \amp= \int_0^2 (1+x)\,dx \amp= \left[ x+\frac12x^2 \right]_0^2 \amp= 2+2 \amp= 4.
Thus the sign has mass \boxed{ m=4\text{ kg}. }

Similarly,
\iint_D y\sigma(x,y)\,dA \amp= \int_0^2\int_0^1 y(1+x)\,dy\,dx \amp= \int_0^2 (1+x) \left[ \frac12y^2 \right]_0^1 dx \amp= \frac12\int_0^2(1+x)\,dx \amp= \frac12\cdot4 \amp= 2.
Thus \bar y=\frac{2}{4}=\frac12. The center of mass is \boxed{ \left(\bar x,\bar y\right)=\left(\frac76,\frac12\right). }

