statement.p:
Let a lamina occupy a region D, with density \sigma(x,y), and total
mass
m=\iint_D \sigma(x,y)\,dA\gt 0.
The moment about the y-axis is
\boxed{ M_y=\iint_D x\,\sigma(x,y)\,dA. }
The moment about the x-axis is
\boxed{ M_x=\iint_D y\,\sigma(x,y)\,dA. }
The center of mass is
\boxed{ \bar x=\frac{M_y}{m}, \qquad \bar y=\frac{M_x}{m}. }

subsection.p:
A point at distance r from the origin contributes a factor r^2. The density is \sigma_0, and dA=r\,dr\,d\theta. So
I_0 \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^a r^2\sigma_0\,r\,dr\,d\theta \amp= \sigma_0\int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^a r^3\,dr\,d\theta \amp= \sigma_0(2\pi) \left[ \frac14r^4 \right]_0^a \amp= \frac{\pi\sigma_0a^4}{2}.
The mass of the disk is m=\sigma_0\pi a^2. Therefore \boxed{ I_0=\frac12ma^2. }

statement.p:
The moment of inertia about the x-axis is
\boxed{ I_x=\iint_D y^2\sigma(x,y)\,dA. }
The moment of inertia about the y-axis is
\boxed{ I_y=\iint_D x^2\sigma(x,y)\,dA. }
The moment of inertia about the origin is
\boxed{ I_0=\iint_D (x^2+y^2)\sigma(x,y)\,dA. }
Since
x^2+y^2
is the squared distance from the origin,
\boxed{ I_0=I_x+I_y. }

subsection.p:
Now find the probability that the dart lands within half the radius: 0\le r\le\frac12. Compute:
P\left(r\le\frac12\right) \amp= \int_0^{2\pi} \int_0^{1/2} \frac{3}{\pi}(1-r)r\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 6\int_0^{1/2}(r-r^2)\,dr \amp= 6\left[ \frac12r^2-\frac13r^3 \right]_0^{1/2} \amp= 6\left( \frac18-\frac1{24} \right) \amp= 6\cdot\frac{2}{24} \amp= \frac12.
So \boxed{ P\left(r\le\frac12\right)=\frac12. }

statement.p:
A function p(x,y) is a probability density on a region
D if
\boxed{ p(x,y)\ge0 }
and
\boxed{ \iint_D p(x,y)\,dA=1. }
For a subregion A\subseteq D,
\boxed{ P((X,Y)\in A)=\iint_A p(x,y)\,dA. }

If f is continuous on a region D with positive area, then the
average value of f over D is
\boxed{ f_{\text{avg}} = \frac{1}{\operatorname{Area}(D)} \iint_D f(x,y)\,dA. }

subsection.p:
The moments of inertia are
\boxed{ I_x=\iint_D y^2\sigma\,dA, \qquad I_y=\iint_D x^2\sigma\,dA, }
and
\boxed{ I_0=\iint_D (x^2+y^2)\sigma\,dA. }
